The `ssl` directory should contain the SSL certificates and keys for your domain. These files are typically generated by Let's Encrypt Certbot when you request a certificate. Here is an example of what the file structure in the `ssl` directory might look like:
```
ssl
├── example.com.crt
├── example.com.key
└── letsencrypt
    ├── accounts
    ├── archive
    ├── csr
    ├── keys
    └── renewal
```
As for the `default.conf.template` file, it should contain the Nginx configuration for your virtual host. Here is an example of what this file might look like:
```
server {
  listen 80;
  listen [::]:80;
  server_name ${NGINX_HOST};
  return 301 https://${NGINX_HOST}$request_uri;
}

server {
  listen 443 ssl http2;
  listen [::]:443 ssl http2;
  server_name ${NGINX_HOST};
  root /app;

  ssl_certificate /etc/nginx/ssl/example.com.crt;
  ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/example.com.key;
  include /etc/nginx/ssl/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf;
  ssl_dhparam /etc/nginx/ssl/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem;

  location / {
    try_files $uri $uri/ /index.php$is_args$args;
  }

  location ~ \.php$ {
    try_files $uri =404;
    fastcgi_pass php:9000;
    fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
    include fastcgi_params;
  }
}
```
In this example, the `${NGINX_HOST}` variable will be replaced with the value of the `NGINX_HOST` environment variable at runtime. This allows you to use the same configuration file for multiple virtual hosts by simply specifying a different value for the `NGINX_HOST` variable in each service.

Yes, you can modify the `default.conf.template` file to include a default host in addition to the virtual host specified by the `${NGINX_HOST}` variable. To do this, you will need to add a new `server` block to the file.

Here is an example of what the modified `default.conf.template` file might look like:
```
server {
  listen 80 default_server;
  listen [::]:80 default_server;
  server_name _;
  return 444;
}

server {
  listen 80;
  listen [::]:80;
  server_name ${NGINX_HOST};
  return 301 https://${NGINX_HOST}$request_uri;
}

server {
  listen 443 ssl http2;
  listen [::]:443 ssl http2;
  server_name ${NGINX_HOST};
  root /app;

  ssl_certificate /etc/nginx/ssl/example.com.crt;
  ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/example.com.key;
  include /etc/nginx/ssl/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf;
  ssl_dhparam /etc/nginx/ssl/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem;

  location / {
    try_files $uri $uri/ /index.php$is_args$args;
  }

  location ~ \.php$ {
    try_files $uri =404;
    fastcgi_pass php:9000;
    fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
    include fastcgi_params;
  }
}
```
In this example, the first `server` block listens on port 80 and responds with a 444 status code for all requests to any host other than the virtual host specified by the `${NGINX_HOST}` variable. The second `server` block redirects all HTTP requests for the virtual host to HTTPS. The third `server` block serves the virtual host over HTTPS.
